1. Node.js: What and Why
Node.js is a JavaScript runtime built on Chrome’s V8 engine.
It allows you to run JavaScript on the server, not just in the browser.
Key points:
Single-threaded, event-driven, non-blocking I/O → good for handling many requests efficiently.
Enables you to write full-stack apps using JavaScript both on front-end (React) and back-end (Node.js/Express).

Example Use Case:

Server-side APIs
Web applications
Real-time applications (chat apps, gaming servers)

Installation (if you weren’t using Docker):

node -v   # check installed Node.js version
npm -v    # check installed npm version
2. npm (Node Package Manager)
npm comes with Node.js.
It is used to manage packages/libraries.
Helps install dependencies needed for React or any Node.js project.

Key Commands:

npm init → create a new Node.js project and package.json
npm install <package> → install a library/package
npm start → run the start script defined in package.json
npm run build → build your React app for production

package.json Example:

{
  "name": "my-app",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "scripts": {
    "start": "react-scripts start",
    "build": "react-scripts build"
  },
  "dependencies": {
    "react": "^18.2.0",
    "react-dom": "^18.2.0"
  }
}
3. React: Front-end Library
React is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces.
Component-based → UI is split into reusable components.
Works well with Node.js backend because both use JavaScript.

React Workflow:

npx create-react-app my-app → creates a boilerplate React project.
npm start → runs development server on port 3000.
npm run build → builds production-ready static files.

React Folder Structure:

my-app/
 ├─ public/        # index.html, static assets
 ├─ src/           # all React components
 │   ├─ App.js
 │   ├─ index.js
 ├─ package.json   # project config
4. Using React with Docker

Why Docker?

Docker allows you to run React in a container, making it independent of your local environment.
Ensures “works on my machine” is true everywhere.

Steps to Use React with Docker After Pulling Node.js Image:

Step 1: Pull Node.js Docker Image
docker pull node:20
node:20 → Node.js version 20 image from Docker Hub.
This image comes with Node.js and npm preinstalled.
Step 2: Create Your React App

You can do this either on host machine or inside a container.

Option 1: On host:

npx create-react-app login-app
cd login-app
npm start
Runs on localhost:3000 (dev server).

Option 2: Inside Docker (recommended for full isolation):

docker run -it --name react-container -v $(pwd):/app -w /app node:20 bash
# inside container shell
npx create-react-app login-app
cd login-app
npm start
-v $(pwd):/app → maps host folder to container
-w /app → sets working directory inside container
Step 3: Create Dockerfile for React App
# Dockerfile
FROM node:20

# Set working directory
WORKDIR /app

# Copy package.json and install dependencies
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install

# Copy all source code
COPY . .

# Expose port
EXPOSE 3000

# Start React app
CMD ["npm", "start"]
Step 4: Build Docker Image
docker build -t react-login-app .
Step 5: Run React Container
docker run -d -p 3000:3000 --name react-login-app-container react-login-app
-d → detached mode (runs in background)
-p 3000:3000 → maps container port 3000 to host 3000
Check logs if needed:
docker logs -f react-login-app-container
Step 6: Edit React Code
If you mounted volume (-v $(pwd):/app), changes in src/App.js on host automatically reflect inside container.
The dev server recompiles on save → live reload.
Key Notes
For production, build React and serve via Nginx instead of npm start for better performance.
npm start inside Docker is mainly for development.
Docker containers with Node.js ensure that all team members run React in the same environment.

✅ Summary of Flow:

Pull Node.js Docker image → docker pull node:20
Create React app → npx create-react-app login-app
Write Dockerfile → define app environment
Build Docker image → docker build -t react-login-app .
Run container → docker run -d -p 3000:3000 react-login-app
Edit code → live reload through volume mount
